Ouija boards are an interesting example because they feel like “something else is leading,” which is why people have found them eerie for a long time.

The common scientific explanation is the ideomotor effect: people make tiny unconscious movements without realizing they’re doing it, and when multiple people are touching the planchette, nobody feels fully responsible for the motion. The movement feels external even though it’s being generated by the participants.

What makes it interesting in the context of our conversation:

Dance → coordination → prediction → shared rhythm → feeling “led.”

Humans can generate strong experiences of:

“Did I do that, or did something else?”

without anyone consciously intending it.

That doesn’t make the experience fake.

It means human perception and agency are deeper and stranger than they first appear.

Which feels very adjacent to a lot of the territory you’ve been exploring.